LOCATION:INDIANA MEMORIAL UNION (UNION BUILDING) - Room Number: Maple Room
GEO:39.167655;-86.523537
SUMMARY:Rethinking the Founding: Asia\, Asian Americans\, and the Making 
 of America
DESCRIPTION:Panelists:Ian Shin (mailto:https://lsa.umich.edu/ac/people/fa
 culty/ianshin.html) (History\, University of Michigan) will discuss turni
 ng points in U.S. history\, through the early 20th and 19th centuries to 
 the American Founding\, with an emphasis on a "Pacific-facing" approach Ō
 Ćō connections to the Asia/Pacific world ŌĆō which offers a more complex\
 , multi-polar view of the nation's past. Dr Shin's newest book isImperial
  Stewards: Chinese Art and the Making of America's Pacific Century (mailt
 o:https://www.sup.org/books/asian-american-studies/imperial-stewards) (St
 anford U Press).Michael Salgarolo (mailto:https://as.nyu.edu/faculty/mich
 ael-salgarolo.html) (Social &amp\; Cultural Analysis\, New York Universit
 y)\, who does work on early Filipino migrants\, who may have been the fir
 st Asians to settle in the U.S. in the 1700s in Louisiana. His research t
 ells the story of Filipino sailors who came to the bayous of Louisiana an
 d how they and their descendants navigated the racial landscape.  To roun
 d out the panel\, Ishan Ashutosh (mailto:https://geography.indiana.edu/ab
 out/faculty/ashutosh-ishan.html) (Geography\, Indiana University-Blooming
 ton) who is an expert on the transnational politics of South Asian diaspo
 ras has agreed to discuss the South Asian perspective\, and he will talk 
 about his research on how the American Revolution influenced Indian natio
 nalists in the United States in the early 20th century.  This event is pr
 esented by the Asian American Studies Program (https://aast.indiana.edu/)
 .&#160\;
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p><strong>Panelists:</strong></p><p><a href
 ="mailto:https://lsa.umich.edu/ac/people/faculty/ianshin.html">Ian Shin</
 a> (History\, University of Michigan) <span class="xelementtoproof"><span
  style="color: black\;">will discuss turning points in U.S. history\, thr
 ough the early 20th and 19th centuries to the American Founding\, with an
  emphasis on a "Pacific-facing" approach ŌĆō connections to the Asia/Paci
 fic world ŌĆō which offers a more complex\, multi-polar view of the natio
 n's past. Dr Shin's newest book is</span></span><a href="mailto:https://w
 ww.sup.org/books/asian-american-studies/imperial-stewards">Imperial Stewa
 rds: Chinese Art and the Making of America's Pacific Century</a> (Stanfor
 d U Press).</p><p><a href="mailto:https://as.nyu.edu/faculty/michael-salg
 arolo.html">Michael Salgarolo</a> (Social &amp\; Cultural Analysis\, New 
 York University)\, who does work on early Filipino migrants\, who may hav
 e been the first Asians to settle in the U.S. in the 1700s in Louisiana. 
 His research tells the story of Filipino sailors who came to the bayous o
 f Louisiana and how they and their descendants navigated the racial lands
 cape.<br /><br />  To round out the panel\, <a href="mailto:https://geogr
 aphy.indiana.edu/about/faculty/ashutosh-ishan.html">Ishan Ashutosh</a> (G
 eography\, Indiana University-Bloomington) who is an expert on the transn
 ational politics of South Asian diasporas has agreed to discuss the South
  Asian perspective\, and he will talk about his research on how the Ameri
 can Revolution influenced Indian nationalists in the United States in the
  early 20th century.<br /><br />  This event is presented by the <a href=
 "https://aast.indiana.edu/">Asian American Studies Program</a>.&#160\;</p
 >
