SUMMARY:CANCELED: Career Skills for Global Students
DESCRIPTION:What makes something worth doing\, creating\, or preserving? 
 In this final session of the CareerSkills for Global Students series\, we
  explore how students in the Humanities and Area Studies engage not only 
 in the interpretation of cultureŌĆöbut in the making of value. Through st
 orytelling\, translation\, curation\, research\, and advocacy\, students 
 shape how people understand what mattersŌĆöethically\, culturally\, and s
 ocially. Whether you're creating a podcast about Korean literature\, tran
 slating activist poetry from Chinese\, or designing a public exhibit on J
 apanese visual culture\, you are generating meaning and relevance for new
  audiences. This session invites you to see your academic work not just a
 s reflective\, but as generative. You're not only learning about the valu
 es of othersŌĆöyou're actively contributing to cultural ecosystems\, publ
 ic understanding\, and the reimagining of what holds worth in our rapidly
  changing world. Join us as we examine how students become value-makers: 
 creators\, communicators\, and curators of what counts.Career Skills for 
 Global Students is a workshop series organized by the East Asian Studies 
 Center in collaboration with the Hamilton Lugar School and the HLS Living
 -Learning Center. Designed to help students translate their classroom exp
 eriencesŌĆöespecially in East Asian Studies and the HumanitiesŌĆöinto pra
 ctical\, future-facing career skills\, the series explores how global kno
 wledge\, cultural insight\, and interdisciplinary thinking prepare studen
 ts to thrive in an ever-changing world of work.Organizer and workshop lea
 der:Morten Oxenboell\, PhD  Director\, East Asian Studies Center (EASC)  
 Director\, National Consortium for Teaching about Asia (NCTA)\, Indiana  
 Associate Professor\, Dept. East Asian Languages and Cultures  Adjunct As
 sociate Professor\, Dept. History  Indiana University  Check out my (free
 !) Substack for my thoughts on current and future state of the Humanities
 : https://valueoftheworthless.substack.com/ (https://valueoftheworthless.
 substack.com/)  Everyone is welcome to attend.
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p>  What makes something worth doing\, crea
 ting\, or preserving? In this final session of the <em>Career</em><em>Ski
 lls for Global Students</em> series\, we explore how students in the Huma
 nities and Area Studies engage not only in the interpretation of cultureŌ
 Ćöbut in the <em>making of value</em>. Through storytelling\, translation
 \, curation\, research\, and advocacy\, students shape how people underst
 and what mattersŌĆöethically\, culturally\, and socially. Whether you're 
 creating a podcast about Korean literature\, translating activist poetry 
 from Chinese\, or designing a public exhibit on Japanese visual culture\,
  you are generating meaning and relevance for new audiences. This session
  invites you to see your academic work not just as reflective\, but as <e
 m>generative</em>. You're not only learning about the values of othersŌĆö
 you're actively contributing to cultural ecosystems\, public understandin
 g\, and the reimagining of what holds worth in our rapidly changing world
 . Join us as we examine how students become value-makers: creators\, comm
 unicators\, and curators of what counts.</p><p><strong>Career Skills for 
 Global Students</strong> is a workshop series organized by the East Asian
  Studies Center in collaboration with the Hamilton Lugar School and the H
 LS Living-Learning Center. Designed to help students translate their clas
 sroom experiencesŌĆöespecially in East Asian Studies and the HumanitiesŌĆ
 öinto practical\, future-facing career skills\, the series explores how g
 lobal knowledge\, cultural insight\, and interdisciplinary thinking prepa
 re students to thrive in an ever-changing world of work.</p><p><strong>Or
 ganizer and workshop leader:<br /></strong>Morten Oxenboell\, PhD<br />  
 Director\, East Asian Studies Center (EASC)<br />  Director\, National Co
 nsortium for Teaching about Asia (NCTA)\, Indiana<br />  Associate Profes
 sor\, Dept. East Asian Languages and Cultures<br />  Adjunct Associate Pr
 ofessor\, Dept. History<br />  Indiana University</p><p>  Check out my (f
 ree!) Substack for my thoughts on current and future state of the Humanit
 ies: <a href="https://valueoftheworthless.substack.com/">https://valueoft
 heworthless.substack.com/</a><br /><br />  Everyone is welcome to attend.
 </p>
